1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,992
Book VI.

2
00:00:01,332 --> 00:00:03,794
The meeting between Nausicaa and Ulysses.

3
00:00:04,395 --> 00:00:15,285
So here Ulysses slept, overcome by sleep and toil, but Minerva went off to the country and city of the Phaeacians, a people who used to live in the fair town of Hyperaia, near the lawless Cyclopes.

4
00:00:15,985 --> 00:00:23,532
Now the Cyclopes were stronger than they and plundered them, so their king Nausihaus moved them thence and settled them in Sheria, far from all other people.

5
00:00:24,013 --> 00:00:30,038
He surrounded the city with a wall, built houses and temples, and divided the lands among his people.

6
00:00:30,018 --> 00:00:37,253
But he was dead and gone to the house of Hades, and King Alcinus, whose counsels were inspired of heaven, was now reigning.

7
00:00:37,934 --> 00:00:42,163
To his house, then, did Minerva hide in furtherance of the return of Ulysses.

8
00:00:42,704 --> 00:00:51,722
She went straight to the beautifully decorated bedroom, in which there slept a girl who was as lovely as a goddess, now Cycaia, daughter to King Alcinus.

9
00:00:51,702 --> 00:00:58,811
Two maidservants were sleeping near her, both very pretty, one on either side of the doorway, which was closed with well-made folding doors.

10
00:00:59,412 --> 00:01:06,281
Minerva took the form of the famous sea captain Demas's daughter, who was a bosom friend of Nausicaa and just her own age.

11
00:01:06,721 --> 00:01:16,714
Then, coming up to the girl's bedside like a breath of wind, she hovered over her head and said, Nausicaa, what can your mother have been about to have such a lazy daughter?

12
00:01:16,694 --> 00:01:26,864
Here are your clothes, all lying in disorder, yet you are going to be married almost immediately, and should not only be well-dressed yourself, but should find good clothes for those who attend you.

13
00:01:27,465 --> 00:01:31,469
This is the way to get yourself a good name, and to make your father and mother proud of you.

14
00:01:32,050 --> 00:01:35,914
Suppose, then, that we make tomorrow a washing day, and start at daybreak.

15
00:01:36,494 --> 00:01:46,144
I will come and help you so that you may have everything ready as soon as possible, for all the best young men among your own people are courting you, and you are not going to remain a maid much longer.

16
00:01:46,124 --> 00:01:59,887
Ask your father, therefore, to have a wagon and mules ready for us at daybreak, to take the rugs, robes, and girdles, and you can ride too, which will be much pleasanter for you than walking, for the washing cisterns are some way from the town."

17
00:02:00,588 --> 00:02:05,917
When she had said this, Minerva went away to Olympus, which they say is the everlasting home of the gods.

18
00:02:06,518 --> 00:02:10,765
Here no wind beats roughly, and neither rain nor snow can fall.

19
00:02:10,745 --> 00:02:18,175
but it abides in everlasting sunshine and in a great peacefulness of light, wherein the blessed gods are illumined for ever and ever."

20
00:02:19,156 --> 00:02:22,961
This was the place to which the goddess went when she had given instructions to the girl.

21
00:02:23,642 --> 00:02:28,228
By and by morning came and woke Nausicaa, who began wondering about her dream.

22
00:02:28,669 --> 00:02:33,976
She therefore went to the other end of the house to tell her father and mother all about it and found them in their own room.

23
00:02:34,737 --> 00:02:39,283
Her mother was sitting by the fireside spinning her purple yarn with her maids around her.

24
00:02:39,483 --> 00:02:43,975
she happened to catch her father just as he was going out to attend a meeting of the town council.

25
00:02:44,225 --> 00:02:46,087
which the Phaeacian aldermen had convened.

26
00:02:46,828 --> 00:02:51,354
She stopped him and said, Papatyr, could you manage to let me have a good big wagon?

27
00:02:51,794 --> 00:02:54,437
I want to take all our dirty clothes to the river and wash them.

28
00:02:55,078 --> 00:03:00,905
You are the chief man here, so it is only right that you should have a clean shirt when you attend meetings of the council.

29
00:03:01,406 --> 00:03:07,353
Moreover, you have five sons at home, two of them married, while the other three are good-looking bachelors.

30
00:03:07,653 --> 00:03:13,540
You know they always like to have clean linen when they go to a dance, and I have been thinking about all this.

31
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:22,231
She did not say a word about her own wedding, for she did not like to, but her father knew and said, You shall have the mules, my love, and whatever else you have a mind for.

32
00:03:22,892 --> 00:03:28,219
Be off with you, and the men shall get you a good strong wagon with a body to it that will hold all your clothes.

33
00:03:28,940 --> 00:03:37,671
On this he gave his orders to the servants, who got the wagon out, harnessed the mules, and put them to, while the girl brought the clothes down from the linen room and placed them on the wagon.

34
00:03:37,651 --> 00:03:43,518
Her mother prepared her a basket of provisions with all sorts of good things, and a goatskin full of wine.

35
00:03:43,918 --> 00:03:50,946
The girl now got into the wagon, and her mother gave her also a golden cruz of oil, that she and her women might anoint themselves.

36
00:03:51,887 --> 00:03:57,974
Then she took the whip and reins and lashed the mules on, whereon they set off, and their hoofs clattered on the road.

37
00:03:58,695 --> 00:04:05,683
They pulled without flagging, and carried not only Nausicaa and her wash of clothes, but the maids also who were with her.

38
00:04:05,866 --> 00:04:14,200
When they reached the waterside they went to the washing cisterns, through which there ran at all times enough pure water to wash any quantity of linen, no matter how dirty.

39
00:04:14,921 --> 00:04:20,330
Here they unharnessed the mules and turned them out to feed on the sweet, juicy herbage that grew by the waterside.

40
00:04:20,831 --> 00:04:27,081
They took the clothes out of the wagon, put them in the water, and vied with one another in treading them in the pits to get the dirt out.

41
00:04:27,061 --> 00:04:37,071
After they had washed them and got them quite clean, they laid them out by the seaside, where the waves had raised a high beach of shingle, and set about washing themselves and anointing themselves with olive oil.

42
00:04:37,422 --> 00:04:41,929
Then they got their dinner by the side of the stream and waited for the sun to finish drying the clothes.

43
00:04:42,590 --> 00:04:48,579
When they had done dinner, they threw off the veils that covered their heads and began to play at ball, while Nausicaa sang for them.

44
00:04:49,220 --> 00:05:05,404
As the huntress Diana goes forth upon the mountains of Tigitus or Erymanthus to hunt wild boars or deer, and the wood nymphs, daughters of Aegis bearing Jove, take their sport along with her, then is Leto proud at seeing her daughter stand a full head taller than the others

45
00:05:05,384 --> 00:05:11,074
and eclipsed the loveliest amid a whole bevy of beauties, even so did the girl outshine her handmaids.

46
00:05:11,696 --> 00:05:22,776
When it was time for them to start home, and they were folding the clothes and putting them into the wagon, Minerva began to consider how Ulysses should wake up and see the handsome girl who was to conduct him to the city of the Phaeacians.

47
00:05:23,537 --> 00:05:28,827
The girl therefore threw a ball at one of the maids, which missed her and fell into deep water.

48
00:05:28,807 --> 00:05:36,317
On this they all shouted, and the noise they made woke Ulysses, who sat up in his bed of leaves and began to wonder what it might all be.

49
00:05:37,379 --> 00:05:37,719
Alas!

50
00:05:38,039 --> 00:05:41,184
said he to himself, what kind of people have I come amongst?

51
00:05:41,744 --> 00:05:45,730
Are they cruel, savage, and uncivilized, or hospitable and humane?

52
00:05:46,431 --> 00:05:51,878
I seem to hear the voices of young women, and they sound like those of the nymphs that haunt mountaintops,

53
00:05:51,858 --> 00:05:54,665
or springs of rivers and meadows of green grass.

54
00:05:55,788 --> 00:05:58,635
At any rate, I am among a race of men and women.

55
00:05:59,257 --> 00:06:01,463
Let me try if I cannot manage to get a look at them."

56
00:06:02,586 --> 00:06:08,922
As he said this, he crept from under his bush and broke off a bough covered with thick leaves to hide his nakedness.

57
00:06:08,902 --> 00:06:15,592
He looked like some lion of the wilderness that stalks about exulting in his strength and defying both wind and rain.

58
00:06:15,953 --> 00:06:26,269
His eyes glare as he prowls in quest of oxen, sheep or deer, for he is famished and will dare break even into a well-fenced homestead, trying to get at the sheep.

59
00:06:26,249 --> 00:06:32,742
Even such did Ulysses seem to the young women, as he drew near to them all naked as he was, for he was in great want.

60
00:06:33,344 --> 00:06:39,937
On seeing one so unkempt and so begrimed with salt water, the others scampered off along the spits that jutted out into the sea.

61
00:06:40,378 --> 00:06:46,671
But the daughter of Alcinous stood firm, for Minerva put courage into her heart and took away all fear from her.

62
00:06:46,651 --> 00:06:59,367
She stood right in front of Ulysses, and he doubted whether he should go up to her, throw himself at her feet, and embrace her knees as a suppliant, or stay where he was and entreat her to give him some clothes and show him the way to the town.

63
00:07:00,188 --> 00:07:10,701
In the end he deemed it best to entreat her from a distance, in case the girl should take offence at his coming near enough to clasp her knees, so he addressed her in honeyed and persuasive language.

64
00:07:10,681 --> 00:07:17,028
O Queen, he said, I implore your aid, but tell me, are you a goddess, or are you a mortal woman?

65
00:07:17,649 --> 00:07:24,958
If you are a goddess and dwell in heaven, I can only conjecture that you are Jove's daughter Diana, for your face and figure resemble none but hers.

66
00:07:25,478 --> 00:07:38,173
If, on the other hand, you are a mortal and live on earth, thrice happy are your father and mother, thrice happy too are your brothers and sisters, how proud and delighted they must feel when they see so fair a scion as yourself going out to a dance.

67
00:07:38,153 --> 00:07:44,127
Most happy, however, of all will he be, whose wedding gifts have been the richest, and who takes you to his own home.

68
00:07:44,868 --> 00:07:50,341
I never yet saw anyone so beautiful, neither man nor woman, and am lost in admiration as I behold you.

69
00:07:50,842 --> 00:07:56,314
I can only compare you to a young palm tree which I saw when I was at Delos growing near the altar of Apollo.

70
00:07:56,294 --> 00:08:01,462
For I was there, too, with much people after me, when I was on that journey which has been the source of all my troubles.

71
00:08:02,023 --> 00:08:05,147
Never yet did such a young plant shoot out of the ground as that was.

72
00:08:05,748 --> 00:08:10,015
And I admired and wondered at it exactly as I now admire and wonder at yourself.

73
00:08:10,576 --> 00:08:13,500
I dare not clasp your knees, but I am in great distress.

74
00:08:13,740 --> 00:08:17,526
Yesterday made the twentieth day that I had been tossing about upon the sea.

75
00:08:17,506 --> 00:08:22,393
The winds and waves have taken me all the way from the Ogygian island, five and fivent.

76
00:08:22,773 --> 00:08:26,979
Now fate has flung me upon this coast, that I may endure still further suffering.

77
00:08:27,560 --> 00:08:33,288
For I do not think that I have yet come to the end of it, but rather that heaven has still much evil in store for me.

78
00:08:34,009 --> 00:08:40,678
And now, O Queen, have pity upon me, for you are the first person I have met, and I know no one else in this country.

79
00:08:41,279 --> 00:08:46,686
Show me the way to your town, and let me have anything that you may have brought hither to wrap your clothes in.

80
00:08:46,666 --> 00:08:49,333
May heaven grant you in all things your heart's desire.

81
00:08:49,814 --> 00:08:52,220
Husband, house, and a happy, peaceful home.

82
00:08:52,500 --> 00:08:56,591
For there is nothing better in this world than that man and wife should be of one mind in a house.

83
00:08:56,971 --> 00:09:02,886
It discomforts their enemies, makes the hearts of their friends glad, and they themselves know more about it than anyone.

84
00:09:03,187 --> 00:09:08,133
To this Nausicaa answered, Stranger, you appear to be a sensible, well-disposed person.

85
00:09:08,654 --> 00:09:10,036
There is no accounting for luck.

86
00:09:10,637 --> 00:09:17,465
Jove gives prosperity to rich and poor just as he chooses, so you must take what he has seen fit to send you, and make the best of it.

87
00:09:18,066 --> 00:09:25,836
Now, however, that you have come to this, our country, you shall not want for clothes nor for anything else that a foreigner in distress may reasonably look for.

88
00:09:26,457 --> 00:09:30,106
I will show you the way to the town, and will tell you the name of our people.

89
00:09:30,326 --> 00:09:35,618
We are called Phaeacians, and I am daughter to Alcinous, in whom the whole power of the state is vested."

90
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:39,608
Then she called her maids and said, "'Stay where you are, you girls.

91
00:09:39,909 --> 00:09:41,973
Can you not see a man without running away from him?

92
00:09:42,294 --> 00:09:44,820
Do you take him for a robber or a murderer?'

93
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:56,734
Neither he nor anyone else can come here to do us Phaeacians any harm, for we are dear to the gods and live apart on a land's end that juts into the sounding sea and have nothing to do with any other people.

94
00:09:57,215 --> 00:10:14,115
This is only some poor man who has lost his way, and we must be kind to him, for strangers and foreigners in distress are under Jove's protection and will take what they can get and be thankful, so, girls, give the poor fellow something to eat and drink and wash him in the stream at some place that is sheltered from the wind.

95
00:10:14,095 --> 00:10:17,659
On this the maids left off running away and began calling one another back.

96
00:10:18,180 --> 00:10:23,286
They made Ulysses sit down in the shelter as NausicaÃ¤ had told them, and brought him a shirt and cloak.

97
00:10:23,887 --> 00:10:28,473
They also brought him the little golden cruz of oil, and told him to go and wash in the stream.

98
00:10:28,973 --> 00:10:42,870
But Ulysses said, Young women, please to stand a little on one side, that I may wash the brine from my shoulders and anoint myself with oil, for it is long enough since my skin has had a drop of oil upon it, I cannot wash as long as you all keep standing there.

99
00:10:42,850 --> 00:10:46,675
I am ashamed to strip fifty-six before a number of good-looking young women."

100
00:10:47,236 --> 00:10:55,186
Then they stood on one side and went to tell the girl, while Ulysses washed himself in the stream and scrubbed the brine from his back and from his broad shoulders.

101
00:10:55,747 --> 00:11:03,017
When he had thoroughly washed himself and had got the brine out of his hair, he anointed himself with oil and put on the clothes which the girl had given him.

102
00:11:03,077 --> 00:11:07,002
Minerva then made him look taller and stronger than before.

103
00:11:06,982 --> 00:11:12,395
She also made the hair grow thick on the top of his head and flow down in curls like hyacinth blossoms.

104
00:11:13,076 --> 00:11:24,383
She glorified him about the head and shoulders as a skillful workman who has studied art of all kinds under Vulcan and Minerva, enriches a piece of silver plate by gilding it, and his work is full of beauty.

105
00:11:24,363 --> 00:11:31,443
Then he went and sat down a little way off upon the beach, looking quite young and handsome, and the girl gazed on him with admiration.

106
00:11:31,744 --> 00:11:35,394
Then she said to her maids, Hush, my dears, for I want to say something.

107
00:11:35,835 --> 00:11:39,385
I believe the gods who live in heaven have sent this man to the Phaeacians.

108
00:11:39,365 --> 00:11:44,635
When I first saw him I thought him plain, but now his appearance is like that of the gods who dwell in heaven.

109
00:11:45,096 --> 00:11:50,667
I should like my future husband to be just such another as he is, if he would only stay here and not want to go away.

110
00:11:51,048 --> 00:11:53,172
However, give him something to eat and drink."

111
00:11:54,114 --> 00:12:01,508
They did as they were told, and set food before Ulysses who ate and drank ravenously, for it was long since he had had food of any kind.

112
00:12:01,488 --> 00:12:04,112
Meanwhile Nausicaa bethought her of another matter.

113
00:12:04,493 --> 00:12:06,757
She got the linen folded and placed in the wagon.

114
00:12:07,177 --> 00:12:10,964
She then yoked the mules, and, as she took her seat, she called Ulysses.

115
00:12:11,605 --> 00:12:15,070
Stranger, said she, rise and let us be going back to the town.

116
00:12:15,571 --> 00:12:21,561
I will introduce you at the house of my excellent father, where I can tell you that you will meet all the best people among the Phaeacians.

117
00:12:22,142 --> 00:12:26,449
But be sure, and do as I bid you, for you seem to be a sensible person.

118
00:12:26,564 --> 00:12:33,575
As long as we are going past the fields and farmlands, follow briskly behind the wagon, along with the maids, and I will lead the way myself.

119
00:12:34,176 --> 00:12:48,317
Presently, however, we shall come to the town, where you will find a high wall running all round it, and a good harbour on either side with a narrow entrance into the city, and the ships will be drawn up by the roadside, for everyone has a place where his own ship can lie.

120
00:12:48,778 --> 00:12:55,288
You will see the marketplace with the temple of Neptune in the middle of it, and paved with large stones bedded in the earth.

121
00:12:55,268 --> 00:13:02,681
Here people deal in ship's gear of all kinds, such as cables and sails, and here too are the places where oars are made.

122
00:13:03,042 --> 00:13:15,083
For the Phaeacians are not a nation of archers, they know nothing about bows and arrows, but are a seafaring folk, and pride themselves on their masts, oars, and ships, with which they travel far over the sea.

123
00:13:15,063 --> 00:13:28,038
I am afraid of the gossip and scandal that may be set on foot against me later on, for the people here are very ill-natured, and some low fellow, if he met us, might say, Who is this fine-looking stranger that is going about with Nausicaa?

124
00:13:28,478 --> 00:13:29,359
Where did she find him?

125
00:13:29,900 --> 00:13:31,262
I suppose she is going to marry him.

126
00:13:31,902 --> 00:13:44,597
Perhaps he is a vagabond sailor whom she has taken from some foreign vessel, for we have no neighbours, or some god has at last come down from heaven in answer to her prayers, and she is going to live with him all the rest of her life.

127
00:13:44,982 --> 00:13:53,055
It would be a good thing if she would take herself off and find a husband somewhere else, for she will not look at one of the many excellent young Phaeacians who are in love with her.

128
00:13:53,896 --> 00:14:09,741
This is the kind of disparaging remark that would be made about me, and I could not complain, for I should myself be scandalized at seeing any other girl do the like and go about with men in spite of everybody, while her father and mother were still alive and without having been married in the face of all the world.

129
00:14:09,721 --> 00:14:19,583
If, therefore, you want my father to give you an escort and to help you home, do as I bid you, you will see a beautiful grove of poplars by the roadside dedicated to Minerva.

130
00:14:20,184 --> 00:14:22,670
It has a well in it and a meadow all round it.

131
00:14:23,411 --> 00:14:29,164
Here my father has a field of rich garden ground, about as far from the town as a man's voice will carry.

132
00:14:29,515 --> 00:14:34,343
Sit down there and wait for a while till the rest of us can get into the town and reach my father's house.

133
00:14:34,884 --> 00:14:40,573
Then, when you think we must have done this, come into the town and ask the way to the house of my father, Alcinous.

134
00:14:40,593 --> 00:14:42,416
You will have no difficulty in finding it.

135
00:14:42,857 --> 00:14:49,127
Any child will point it out to you, for no one else in the whole town has anything like such a fine house as he has."

136
00:14:49,107 --> 00:14:54,519
When you have got past the gates and through the outer court, go right across the inner court till you come to my mother.

137
00:14:55,041 --> 00:14:58,789
You will find her sitting by the fire and spinning her purple wool by firelight.

138
00:14:59,370 --> 00:15:05,344
It is a fine sight to see her as she leans back against one of the bearing posts with her maids all ranged behind her.

139
00:15:05,324 --> 00:15:10,032
Close to her seat stands that of my father, on which he sits and topes like an immortal god.

140
00:15:10,733 --> 00:15:15,400
Never mind him, but go up to my mother and lay your hands upon her knees if you would get home quickly.

141
00:15:16,141 --> 00:15:21,570
If you can gain her over, you may hope to see your own country again, no matter how distant it may be."

142
00:15:22,271 --> 00:15:25,577
So saying, she lashed the mules with her whip, and they left the river.

143
00:15:26,218 --> 00:15:30,184
The mules drew well, and their hooves went up and down upon the road.

144
00:15:30,164 --> 00:15:37,756
She was careful not to go too fast for Ulysses and the maids who were following on foot along with the wagon, so she plied her whip with judgment.

145
00:15:38,417 --> 00:15:46,429
As the sun was going down, they came to the sacred grove of Minerva, and there Ulysses sat down and prayed to the mighty daughter of Jove.

146
00:15:46,890 --> 00:15:55,463
Hear me, he cried, daughter of Aegis bearing Jove, unweariable, hear me now, for you gave no heed to my prayers when Neptune was wrecking me.

147
00:15:55,443 --> 00:16:02,184
Now, therefore, have pity upon me and grant that I may find friends and be hospitably received by the Phaeacians."

148
00:16:02,204 --> 00:16:12,878
Thus did he pray, and Minerva heard his prayer, but she would not show herself to him openly, for she was afraid of her uncle Neptune, who was still furious in his endeavors to prevent Ulysses from getting home.

